The article discusses Russia's recent decision to open its markets but with several restrictions that make it more of a charade than a real market opening. Only 15% of listed shares are allowed to trade, foreigners are prohibited from selling their shares, and short selling is banned. Additionally, Russia has stated its intention to use government resources to artificially prop up the shares of certain companies. The article argues that this is not a sustainable model and highlights Russia's isolation from the global financial system. The United States and its allies plan to continue taking actions to further isolate Russia from the international economic order due to its ongoing war against Ukraine.